518
00:25:16,233 --> 00:25:19,070
Scott: Well, I mean, first you got to understand the history of USB, right?

519
00:25:19,151 --> 00:25:27,708
Scott: Back in the day, as late as the late '90s, when you wanted to plug something into your computer, there were a hundred different kinds of things you could plug in.

520
00:25:27,890 --> 00:25:29,130
Scott: And we're just talking about the outside.

521
00:25:29,290 --> 00:25:29,809
Rym: No inside shit.

522
00:25:29,890 --> 00:25:31,130
Scott: We're talking external cables.

523
00:25:31,250 --> 00:25:32,190
Scott: You had PS/2 cables.

524
00:25:33,212 --> 00:25:35,727
Rym: You had parallel cables, serial ports.

525
00:25:36,230 --> 00:25:38,650
Rym: Most computers did not have parallel ports.

526
00:25:38,830 --> 00:25:39,509
Scott: We had parallel ports.

527
00:25:39,991 --> 00:25:48,970
Rym: Yeah, usually you had to buy a card that was often a combination parallel port card, sound card.

528
00:25:49,430 --> 00:25:53,329
Scott: Well, no, the sound card would have a game port on it, which I didn't meant, right?

529
00:25:53,671 --> 00:25:57,670
Scott: And then there was SCSI on some computers, like RAM with the SCSI-ness.

530
00:25:57,890 --> 00:25:59,530
Rym: I paid a lot of money for that fucking SCSI-ness.

531
00:25:59,730 --> 00:26:00,867
Scott: Right, and that was just PCs.

532
00:26:01,870 --> 00:26:03,369
Scott: Apple computers had a whole bunch of others, right?

533
00:26:04,551 --> 00:26:11,450
Scott: And in those days also, when you connected hardware to a computer, you had to manually configure like the IRQ and whatnot.

534
00:26:11,891 --> 00:26:13,390
Scott: So you had all these problems.

535
00:26:13,490 --> 00:26:23,349
Scott: And what happened was is around the time that Windows 95, 98 came out, they solved the problem of detecting, automatically detecting what was plugged in.

536
00:26:23,490 --> 00:26:25,550
Scott: So you didn't have to manually configure your shit.

537
00:26:25,650 --> 00:26:27,185
Scott: It would just be like, "Oh, I see some hardware.

538
00:26:27,225 --> 00:26:27,346
Scott: All

539
00:26:27,387 --> 00:26:27,548
Scott: good.".

540
00:26:27,831 --> 00:26:28,889
Rym: That was a big deal.

541
00:26:29,130 --> 00:26:30,530
Scott: Right, it was called Plug and Play, right?

542
00:26:30,530 --> 00:26:31,528
Scott: And it actually started to work.

543
00:26:32,251 --> 00:26:38,149
Scott: And they could load the drivers for your hardware dynamically instead of you having to manually put them in.

544
00:26:38,810 --> 00:26:43,949
Scott: So that allowed for the introduction of USB, the Universal Serial Bus.

545
00:26:44,372 --> 00:26:49,990
Scott: They could replace pretty much almost all of those ports with one kind of port, the USB.

546
00:26:50,710 --> 00:26:55,805
Scott: And the most important thing about USB is that you could plug and unplug something while the computer was on.

547
00:26:56,270 --> 00:26:58,049
Scott: You didn't have to detect it when it turned on.

548
00:26:58,710 --> 00:27:04,148
Scott: You used to have to like, if you want to plug something new into your computer, you'd have to turn your computer off, plug something in, turn the computer on.

549
00:27:05,091 --> 00:27:06,329
Scott: Not USB, you don't do that shit.

550
00:27:06,990 --> 00:27:07,438
Rym: Huge difference.

551
00:27:07,479 --> 00:27:07,621
Rym: Huge.

552
00:27:08,090 --> 00:27:08,740
Rym: So imagine this.

553
00:27:08,861 --> 00:27:09,450
Rym: Here's an example.

554
00:27:09,530 --> 00:27:11,529
Rym: In the old days, I was at a LAN party, right?

555
00:27:12,075 --> 00:27:12,950
Rym: In Southfield.

556
00:27:13,312 --> 00:27:14,490
Rym: And I went with a bunch of my friends.

557
00:27:14,571 --> 00:27:16,650
Rym: We'd respect our giant fucking CRTs.

558
00:27:17,210 --> 00:27:18,949
Rym: Everyone rode with a CRT in their lap.

559
00:27:19,750 --> 00:27:21,910
Rym: We go to this LAN party, we hook everything up, we play.

560
00:27:22,373 --> 00:27:26,189
Rym: In the middle of a tournament, I kicked my keyboard cable out.

561
00:27:26,490 --> 00:27:27,209
Scott: You had to restart your computer.

562
00:27:27,330 --> 00:27:28,250
Rym: I had to reboot my computer.

563
00:27:29,155 --> 00:27:30,530
Rym: You can't just plug that shit back in.

564
00:27:30,610 --> 00:27:30,928
Scott: That's right.

565
00:27:31,750 --> 00:27:35,747
Rym: So all these methods were very, very simple.

566
00:27:37,373 --> 00:27:41,369
Rym: The way these ports worked was so simple that you would almost laugh at them today.

567
00:27:41,793 --> 00:27:46,070
Rym: Serial ports had all these pins that had all these different functions.

568
00:27:46,530 --> 00:27:52,489
Rym: You could make a circuit that would respond to a serial port out of resistors and a breadboard.

569
00:27:53,110 --> 00:27:54,649
Rym: Like you, right now, could just do that.

570
00:27:54,952 --> 00:27:55,790
Rym: It was so simple.

571
00:27:56,310 --> 00:27:59,148
Rym: Maybe a big chip with a bunch of NAND gates on it to make it easier.

572
00:28:00,130 --> 00:28:03,550
Rym: Parallel ports, in theory, were faster than serial ports.

573
00:28:03,612 --> 00:28:04,029
Scott: In theory.

574
00:28:04,530 --> 00:28:07,130
Rym: Because serial ports were serial.

575
00:28:07,631 --> 00:28:09,710
Rym: They said one bit at a time.

576
00:28:09,751 --> 00:28:11,210
Scott: Just like a serial TV show.

577
00:28:11,410 --> 00:28:12,130
Scott: Things in order.

578
00:28:12,751 --> 00:28:14,230
Scott: So USB is serial.

579
00:28:14,430 --> 00:28:19,050
Scott: It sends one bit at a time, basically, but the bits come in so fast, one after the other.

580
00:28:19,150 --> 00:28:22,190
Scott: A parallel port can send multiple bits simultaneously.

581
00:28:22,650 --> 00:28:25,910
Scott: Like, here are eight bits, and they all arrive at the same exact moment.

582
00:28:26,070 --> 00:28:27,479
Scott: So it's like having eight USB ports.

583
00:28:29,250 --> 00:28:31,050
Scott: That should be eight times faster, right?

584
00:28:31,810 --> 00:28:32,030
Scott: Right?

585
00:28:32,651 --> 00:28:35,829
Rym: Well, it was until you started clocking up the speed.

586
00:28:36,192 --> 00:28:43,030
Rym: Because it turns out that in all signaling, one, it actually takes time for the voltage.

587
00:28:43,393 --> 00:28:47,950
Rym: Because remember, signals, as we talked about, god, like five years ago on GeekNights.

588
00:28:48,593 --> 00:28:51,370
Rym: If you want to send a one, you have to agree mutually on both sides.

589
00:28:52,011 --> 00:28:52,730
Rym: What is a one?

590
00:28:53,090 --> 00:28:53,970
Scott: Five volts is a one.

591
00:28:54,410 --> 00:28:54,490
Rym: Yes.

592
00:28:54,730 --> 00:28:57,990
Rym: So your voltage changes to determine ones and zeros.

593
00:28:58,071 --> 00:28:59,989
Rym: There's different encoding mechanisms for that.

594
00:29:00,472 --> 00:29:05,850
Rym: But it takes time for the voltage to get to the threshold and then get to the other threshold.

595
00:29:06,210 --> 00:29:07,629
Scott: It's like the voltage is at zero.

596
00:29:08,012 --> 00:29:13,350
Scott: It goes up to five, which means it was at one at some point, and at two at some point, and at three at some point.

597
00:29:13,973 --> 00:29:16,769
Scott: It's pretty fast when it switches up to five and down to zero again.

598
00:29:17,230 --> 00:29:24,069
Scott: But it takes longer than zero seconds to get the voltage up and then bring it back down again.

599
00:29:24,310 --> 00:29:30,130
Rym: So essentially, what happened was with parallel communication, the same thing happened with IDE and hard drives.

600
00:29:30,850 --> 00:29:35,509
Rym: Parallel data transfers are very difficult to synchronize at high speed.

601
00:29:35,992 --> 00:29:41,170
Rym: All eight of those wires have to be sending at the exact same timing or the whole thing breaks down.

602
00:29:41,350 --> 00:29:48,790
Scott: And by adding technology to keep that stuff synchronized, you're actually just -- that's time taking away from -- It increases complexity.

603
00:29:49,190 --> 00:29:49,950
Rym: It increases cost.

604
00:29:50,150 --> 00:29:52,110
Rym: It increases a lot of issues.

605
00:29:52,270 --> 00:29:57,530
Scott: You could just send one bit at a time really, really fast and just forget about trying to synchronize anything.

606
00:29:57,650 --> 00:30:03,630
Scott: Instead of using some hardware to synchronize stuff, that hardware can just send more bits faster and read more bits faster.

607
00:30:03,791 --> 00:30:06,328
Rym: Remember the background in PETA, parallel ATA.

608
00:30:07,432 --> 00:30:09,830
Rym: Hard drives used to connect with those ribbon cables.

609
00:30:09,930 --> 00:30:10,390
Scott: That's right.

610
00:30:12,030 --> 00:30:17,110
Rym: And then SATA stands for serial ATA, serial one bit at a time.

611
00:30:17,430 --> 00:30:20,750
Scott: And notice how the cable is so much smaller because, yeah, it's only sending one bit at a time.

612
00:30:20,790 --> 00:30:23,530
Scott: You don't need a million cables if you're only sending one at a time.

613
00:30:23,630 --> 00:30:28,050
Scott: All those cables are all to send simultaneous bits on separate wires.

614
00:30:28,350 --> 00:30:31,110
Scott: If you're only sending one wire has the bits on it, well, two technically.

615
00:30:32,133 --> 00:30:35,650
Scott: Then the cables are much smaller for everything and easier to plug in.

616
00:30:35,791 --> 00:30:37,230
Scott: and just everything is just better.

617
00:30:37,450 --> 00:30:42,130
Rym: Now, you might be saying, but Black Dynamite, couldn't I send more than one bit at the same time over one cable?

618
00:30:43,970 --> 00:30:47,510
Rym: Well, you sort of can, but then you have another level of complication.

619
00:30:47,670 --> 00:30:49,109
Rym: For example, in radio signals, there's what?

620
00:30:50,610 --> 00:30:52,730
Rym: QAM, quadratic amplitude modulation.

621
00:30:53,412 --> 00:30:56,210
Rym: This is getting back into like my freshman year of RIT stuff.

622
00:30:56,650 --> 00:31:04,830
Rym: Basically, you could have an encoding mechanism that says something like, if I get up to five volts, it's one, it's zero zero.

623
00:31:05,230 --> 00:31:09,470
Rym: But if I get up to ten volts plus ten, then it's zero one.

624
00:31:09,890 --> 00:31:11,420
Rym: And you could come up with an encoding scheme.

625
00:31:12,210 --> 00:31:12,290
Scott: Yep.

626
00:31:12,690 --> 00:31:16,850
Rym: But now it takes longer to get to all those different voltage states.

627
00:31:16,850 --> 00:31:19,690
Scott: Yeah, to go from zero to ten takes a long ass time.

628
00:31:20,151 --> 00:31:26,730
Rym: And also you have to get to them reliably so that the other side understands, was that a one zero or a one one?

629
00:31:27,013 --> 00:31:27,081
Rym: Yep.

630
00:31:27,150 --> 00:31:32,230
Rym: And you have all the same problem, well, not the same problems, but the same order of problems that you get with a parallel cable.

631
00:31:32,550 --> 00:31:33,050
Scott: Now you could.

632
00:31:33,572 --> 00:31:39,850
Scott: Well, if we could just make serial cables so fast, why don't we just have ten serial cables hooked up to one hard drive?

633
00:31:40,030 --> 00:31:41,149
Scott: And it's like, sure, you can do that.

634
00:31:41,390 --> 00:31:44,270
Rym: Yeah, if you have an asynchronous way of getting at the data you want.

635
00:31:44,310 --> 00:31:45,809
Scott: None of those will be synchronized.

636
00:31:46,110 --> 00:31:48,630
Scott: One of them might be going slightly faster or slower than the other ones.

637
00:31:48,750 --> 00:31:58,150
Scott: You need beyond on the other side of the cables, you need some kind of software or something working at a higher level to sort of resynchronize all the data and put it together.

638
00:31:58,251 --> 00:32:04,750
Scott: It's like, you know, if one of the cables sends you like a hundred bits and the other one is only sent one bit, you need to keep that shit in line somewhere.

639
00:32:04,892 --> 00:32:06,087
Scott: And if you can do it, you can do it.

640
00:32:06,710 --> 00:32:07,705
Rym: Now think about it, something like...

641
00:32:08,030 --> 00:32:12,790
Scott: But then suddenly your CPU is doing this work, putting data back together instead of actually processing that data.

642
00:32:12,870 --> 00:32:21,990
Rym: To use a far flung example, BitTorrent, against a bunch of stuff from a bunch of different sources and puts it together in one contiguous file, because you don't care about latency.

643
00:32:22,432 --> 00:32:22,542
Scott: Nope.

644
00:32:22,850 --> 00:32:25,370
Rym: You can wait, you don't need it in real time.

645
00:32:25,451 --> 00:32:30,550
Rym: It turns out with a mouse or a keyboard, latency matters a lot.

646
00:32:31,271 --> 00:32:36,629
Rym: If you click and something doesn't immediately react, you're frustrated immediately, at least you should be.

