00:33:22,392 --> 00:33:27,310
Scott: But it was like when they started actually making hardware that used it, people were, you know, it's actually caught on.

660
00:33:27,551 --> 00:33:38,170
Scott: And I think really what made it catch on is that almost all the people who had mice and keyboards started making USB mice and keyboards, and they always included in the package a USB to PS2 adapter.

661
00:33:38,492 --> 00:33:54,450
Scott: So, it's like because that was able to exist, the USB to PS2 adapter was such a simple and cheap device, that that's what allowed everyone to switch to making USB mice and keyboards just in throwing these adapters in the package, so that, you know, USB adoption actually happened, right?

662
00:33:54,550 --> 00:34:04,370
Scott: Otherwise, all the people who made mice and keyboards would have kept making PS2 mice and keyboards and USB mice and keyboards separately, and you wouldn't have had people all switching over as much as they did.

663
00:34:05,331 --> 00:34:09,170
Rym: So, the way USB works, you don't care about the signaling.

664
00:34:09,730 --> 00:34:14,924
Rym: Now, this is where I want to talk about the details, because I think a lot of people who think they're using USB 3 aren't.

665
00:34:16,531 --> 00:34:16,844
Rym: No kidding.

666
00:34:17,210 --> 00:34:26,476
Rym: Because I went around showing a lot of people what USB 3 cables look like, and everyone I showed these to, without exception, said, "Whoa, what's that?

667
00:34:26,898 --> 00:34:29,148
Rym: Some kind of proprietary USB

668
00:34:29,168 --> 00:34:29,590
Rym: bullshit?".

669
00:34:29,831 --> 00:34:32,030
Rym: I was like, "No, that's USB 3.

670
00:34:32,030 --> 00:34:34,087
Rym: You clearly are not using it on any device you

671
00:34:34,228 --> 00:34:34,309
Rym: own.".

672
00:34:34,710 --> 00:34:35,295
Scott: I'm using it.

673
00:34:35,355 --> 00:34:40,830
Scott: I have a USB 3 USB stick, and I have a USB 3 holes on my computer.

674
00:34:41,690 --> 00:34:51,150
Rym: Now, the difference is that actually there's different numbers of pins, and there's different kinds of connectors, partly to allow for backward compatibility.

675
00:34:51,610 --> 00:34:52,290
Rym: We'll get to that in a minute.

676
00:34:52,991 --> 00:34:55,989
Rym: So, USB 2 is what most people use and know about.

677
00:34:56,130 --> 00:34:58,070
Rym: That's the USB that was useful.

678
00:34:59,291 --> 00:35:01,449
Scott: It's just faster than USB 1, pretty much.

679
00:35:02,232 --> 00:35:06,590
Rym: The big revolution in USB was that, one, it was serial, which was better because it could extend.

680
00:35:06,730 --> 00:35:08,250
Rym: It could get faster over time.

681
00:35:08,390 --> 00:35:10,709
Scott: You could unplug and plug things in while the computer was on.

682
00:35:10,850 --> 00:35:11,045
Rym: Yup.

683
00:35:11,857 --> 00:35:12,270
Scott: Hot swapping.

684
00:35:12,350 --> 00:35:15,590
Rym: And it could provide power to devices.

685
00:35:15,850 --> 00:35:17,310
Scott: That is the super important thing.

686
00:35:17,330 --> 00:35:25,169
Scott: It used to be when you had a serial cable or a parallel cable or any other kind of cable, you would have to -- PS/2 cables provided enough power to light those little lights.

687
00:35:25,833 --> 00:35:30,309
Scott: Yeah, PS/2 provided enough power for your mouse and keyboard, but that's not enough power to actually do anything, right?

688
00:35:31,351 --> 00:35:39,850
Scott: If you couldn't charge an iPhone from a PS/2 port, if you bought a hard drive that used a serial cable, you had to plug that hard drive into the wall.

689
00:35:40,571 --> 00:35:51,390
Scott: Even when I had a USB 56K modem, that modem had a separate thing to plug into the wall to get power and then a separate thing for the phone cable, right?

690
00:35:51,610 --> 00:35:53,309
Scott: It didn't get all its power just from USB.

691
00:35:54,030 --> 00:36:04,209
Rym: So, kids, if you ever plugged your iPad into a USB port and it wouldn't charge, you didn't understand why, turns out the different versions of USB, as time went on, supported different amounts of power.

692
00:36:04,773 --> 00:36:08,725
Rym: And there's actually a negotiation for, "Hey, device, how much power can you

693
00:36:08,786 --> 00:36:09,169
Rym: handle?".

694
00:36:09,451 --> 00:36:12,286
Rym: "Hey, computer, I can handle five amps.

695
00:36:12,446 --> 00:36:12,668
Rym: Let's

696
00:36:12,708 --> 00:36:12,909
Rym: go.".

697
00:36:13,271 --> 00:36:14,038
Scott: You can't have five amps.

698
00:36:14,078 --> 00:36:19,050
Scott: Pretty much most USB today, almost every USB you're going to encounter is going to be one amp, right?

699
00:36:19,411 --> 00:36:21,149
Scott: Which is enough to charge a lot of things.

700
00:36:21,472 --> 00:36:26,510
Scott: But an iPad is probably the most popular device that will only charge if it sees two amps.

701
00:36:26,631 --> 00:36:29,670
Scott: And almost every USB port you encounter will only be able to provide one.

702
00:36:30,252 --> 00:36:44,750
Scott: So you need to use the Apple given charger to charge your iPad or get a charger that has specifically USB two-amp ports on it and it'll probably have a cable to, you know, a power cable to plug into the wall to get extra juice to power those ports.

703
00:36:45,010 --> 00:36:47,590
Scott: I bought pretty much the best one of these that you can buy.

704
00:36:48,151 --> 00:36:52,690
Scott: And it only has two two-amp ports and two one-amp ports for charging USB devices.

705
00:36:53,251 --> 00:36:56,770
Scott: Because think about it, that's already four, five, six amps.

706
00:36:57,251 --> 00:36:58,035
Scott: That's a lot.

707
00:36:58,055 --> 00:37:04,570
Scott: So, you know, if you made one that was like, you know, like ten two-amp ports, that's 20 amps, you could kill yourself with that.

708
00:37:05,236 --> 00:37:05,358
Rym: Yeah.

709
00:37:05,439 --> 00:37:08,510
Rym: So speaking of killing yourself, here's the part that people don't seem to get.

710
00:37:08,771 --> 00:37:11,428
Rym: There's four pins on standard two USB two.

711
00:37:12,411 --> 00:37:13,555
Rym: Don't worry about USB.

712
00:37:13,776 --> 00:37:17,070
Rym: one is effectively, like it's all backward compatible.

713
00:37:17,250 --> 00:37:18,079
Rym: It all just kind of works.

714
00:37:18,100 --> 00:37:18,949
Rym: You don't need to worry about it.

715
00:37:19,310 --> 00:37:19,995
Rym: There's four pins.

716
00:37:20,941 --> 00:37:22,210
Rym: Two of those pins are for data.

717
00:37:23,810 --> 00:37:26,829
Rym: Because it sends the same data over both pins.

718
00:37:27,270 --> 00:37:27,530
Rym: Opposite.

719
00:37:27,810 --> 00:37:28,012
Rym: Yes.

720
00:37:28,073 --> 00:37:29,448
Rym: The same way ethernet cables do.

721
00:37:29,690 --> 00:37:33,850
Scott: So you have two cables and on cable, if you want to send a one from one end to the other.

722
00:37:33,910 --> 00:37:38,530
Scott: If I want to send Rym a one, we have two basically cups on strings, right?

723
00:37:38,590 --> 00:37:39,715
Scott: I want to send them a one.

724
00:37:40,016 --> 00:37:43,210
Scott: So on the left cup, I say one and the right cup, I say zero.

725
00:37:43,730 --> 00:37:47,170
Scott: And on his end, he gets a one on the left cup and a zero on the right cup.

726
00:37:47,290 --> 00:37:47,810
Scott: And he's like, aha.

727
00:37:48,252 --> 00:37:49,970
Rym: Now that works because of math.

728
00:37:50,171 --> 00:37:54,810
Rym: If you send the same signal with the opposite, so one's plus ten and one's minus ten.

729
00:37:55,050 --> 00:37:56,390
Rym: Just to give you some egregious example.

730
00:37:56,791 --> 00:37:58,950
Rym: That's the point where you're sending your data.

731
00:37:59,511 --> 00:38:06,390
Rym: Then if there's interference, it'll push both of those waves in the same direction because the cables are right next to each other.

732
00:38:07,071 --> 00:38:11,330
Rym: So as a result, you can mathematically eliminate the noise at the other end.

733
00:38:11,570 --> 00:38:11,711
Scott: Right.

734
00:38:11,751 --> 00:38:15,290
Scott: So something happens that ruins the signal there.

735
00:38:15,450 --> 00:38:18,069
Scott: It's like, OK, I sent a one on cup one, so it'll become a two.

736
00:38:19,672 --> 00:38:22,069
Scott: And the zero on the other cup will become like a negative one.

737
00:38:22,771 --> 00:38:26,110
Scott: And if I go, he'll get it on the other end and be like, oh, all right, that should have been a one.

738
00:38:26,230 --> 00:38:27,146
Scott: These both got boosted up.

739
00:38:27,370 --> 00:38:27,434
Scott: Yep.

740
00:38:27,890 --> 00:38:28,132
Rym: Right.

741
00:38:28,152 --> 00:38:31,329
Scott: They got pushed away from each other or toward, you know.

742
00:38:32,873 --> 00:38:35,950
Rym: So USB can deliver a lot of power.

743
00:38:36,071 --> 00:38:38,330
Rym: I mean, powered USB, which I'll talk about in a second.

744
00:38:38,732 --> 00:38:40,150
Rym: I just looked up because I forgot how much.

745
00:38:40,891 --> 00:38:46,310
Rym: It operates on a 48 volt DC and can send up to 25 fucking watts.

746
00:38:46,971 --> 00:38:47,133
Scott: Whoa.

747
00:38:47,678 --> 00:38:48,729
Scott: That's enough for speakers, yo.

748
00:38:49,310 --> 00:38:49,990
Rym: There's crazy stuff.

749
00:38:50,010 --> 00:38:53,450
Scott: I mean, they have USB monitors now, so you can get some serious power out of it.

750
00:38:53,713 --> 00:38:55,410
Rym: Well, powered USB is special, so we'll get to that.

751
00:38:55,470 --> 00:38:57,309
Rym: That's not something that uses extra pins.

752
00:38:57,490 --> 00:38:58,790
Scott: It's like power over ethernet power.

753
00:38:59,893 --> 00:39:01,269
Rym: Actually, yes, it's very related to that.

754
00:39:01,872 --> 00:39:06,790
Rym: So those four pins, the other two pins are one's ground and one's power.

755
00:39:06,950 --> 00:39:08,169
Rym: It's actually really simple.

