00:40:12,771 --> 00:40:17,389
Scott: You're talking about taking the end where the light bulb is and plugging that into the wall also.

785
00:40:17,570 --> 00:40:25,669
Rym: Well, you can't make a loop between the two prongs either using standard cables because no matter what you plug things into, you'll never get a loop.

786
00:40:26,531 --> 00:40:28,843
Rym: You can't get a loop with normal cables.

787
00:40:29,204 --> 00:40:30,370
Rym: in a way that would be meaningful.

788
00:40:30,470 --> 00:40:34,970
Scott: You could go and make a cable that has prongs on one end and prongs on the other end and plug them both into the wall.

789
00:40:35,150 --> 00:40:35,494
Scott: And you know what?

790
00:40:35,514 --> 00:40:37,010
Rym: People die every year doing that.

791
00:40:37,352 --> 00:40:38,508
Rym: You know what the use case is?

792
00:40:39,071 --> 00:40:39,408
Scott: Suicide?

793
00:40:39,810 --> 00:40:40,676
Scott: No, no.

794
00:40:40,777 --> 00:40:41,583
Rym: It's something you're going to go,

795
00:40:41,603 --> 00:40:42,067
Rym: "Uh-oh.".

796
00:40:42,631 --> 00:40:47,244
Rym: Every year, in fact, if you go to Home Depot around Christmas, you'll see signs saying, "Never do

797
00:40:47,284 --> 00:40:47,466
Rym: this.".

798
00:40:48,194 --> 00:40:48,990
Scott: Oh, Christmas lights?

799
00:40:49,130 --> 00:41:00,226
Rym: Yes, because people will string up Christmas lights the wrong way, be done, realize they can't plug their shit in, and rather than unwind all the cables, they'll stick a plug-to-plug adapter.

800
00:41:00,266 --> 00:41:03,890
Rym: in the end, and thus at the top of their tree is a death spike.

801
00:41:05,430 --> 00:41:07,269
Rym: Lots of people get killed by that every year.

802
00:41:08,470 --> 00:41:09,787
Rym: So USB has the same thing.

803
00:41:11,152 --> 00:41:13,430
Rym: USB-A does not mean anything special.

804
00:41:13,610 --> 00:41:16,630
Rym: USB-A is the connector that you plug into your computer.

805
00:41:17,010 --> 00:41:19,870
Rym: It's the USB thing that you know, the rectangle.

806
00:41:20,811 --> 00:41:26,609
Rym: The USB-A socket is what you plug into, and the USB-A socket is where power comes from.

807
00:41:27,913 --> 00:41:30,027
Rym: It's where the controlling device is.

808
00:41:30,812 --> 00:41:31,710
Rym: It's the computer.

809
00:41:32,190 --> 00:41:34,889
Rym: Whatever counts as the computer is USB-A.

810
00:41:36,092 --> 00:41:38,910
Rym: USB-B is whatever you plug that computer into.

811
00:41:39,471 --> 00:41:40,399
Rym: That's the device.

812
00:41:40,762 --> 00:41:41,670
Rym: That's the hard drive.

813
00:41:42,010 --> 00:41:47,329
Rym: So that little square guy that you plug into printers, that's the reason you have two different cables.

814
00:41:47,592 --> 00:41:48,589
Rym: Yeah, the big square one.

815
00:41:49,153 --> 00:41:53,149
Rym: The thing you plug into a printer or a scanner, or like a shitty old phone.

816
00:41:53,992 --> 00:42:01,769
Rym: Actually, I don't think any phone used B. I can't imagine a phone that used B. Mostly printers and scanners and hard drives back in the day.

817
00:42:02,310 --> 00:42:09,610
Rym: That's B. That way, you'll never plug a computer into itself and cause the voltage to hit itself and short out.

818
00:42:09,910 --> 00:42:11,689
Rym: You'll never cause an electrical loop.

819
00:42:11,950 --> 00:42:15,050
Scott: But what if I just want to connect two computers to each other with a USB cable?

820
00:42:15,290 --> 00:42:16,017
Rym: You fucking can't.

821
00:42:16,037 --> 00:42:17,330
Rym: It's not designed for that.

822
00:42:17,630 --> 00:42:19,969
Rym: The architecture is not designed to do that.

823
00:42:20,316 --> 00:42:20,890
Scott: That's sad.

824
00:42:21,170 --> 00:42:22,689
Rym: Now, you could have designed it that way.

825
00:42:23,090 --> 00:42:26,167
Rym: You could have had computers have A's and B's.

