911
00:47:58,930 --> 00:48:01,110
Rym: So there's even further specifications.

912
00:48:01,330 --> 00:48:03,571
Rym: There's nine pins in USB 3.

913
00:48:03,571 --> 00:48:07,630
Rym: Powered USB 3 that can give a shit ton of power has two additional pins.

914
00:48:08,370 --> 00:48:09,010
Rym: Now here's the difference.

915
00:48:09,150 --> 00:48:10,689
Rym: USB 3 isn't just faster.

916
00:48:11,731 --> 00:48:13,990
Rym: It also is bi-directional.

917
00:48:14,410 --> 00:48:14,888
Scott: Full duplex.

918
00:48:15,452 --> 00:48:17,190
Rym: USB 2 is not full duplex, shit guys.

919
00:48:17,491 --> 00:48:19,369
Rym: You can't send and receive data at the same time.

920
00:48:19,710 --> 00:48:21,570
Scott: Yeah, only one talker at a time.

921
00:48:21,650 --> 00:48:22,510
Scott: This is a big deal.

922
00:48:23,332 --> 00:48:28,350
Scott: We used to have an ethernet hub in college that was not full duplex, and that's why it was so cheap.

923
00:48:29,050 --> 00:48:34,970
Scott: And basically it means that if I'm talking to you, you can't talk until I stop talking, and then you can talk again.

924
00:48:35,130 --> 00:48:40,790
Rym: That's why CDMA in ethernet stands for collision detection multiple access.

925
00:48:41,431 --> 00:48:45,329
Rym: So you would listen for collisions because sometimes two people would collide with each other.

926
00:48:45,870 --> 00:48:53,530
Rym: But with modern switches with full duplex, there's no such thing as collisions because there's only one computer on any given segment.

927
00:48:53,671 --> 00:49:01,270
Scott: So with USB 3, let's say you had a hard drive and you were reading data from the hard drive, like a USB stick, you couldn't write data to the hard drive at the same time.

928
00:49:01,391 --> 00:49:03,550
Scott: You had to wait for the reading to be done and then do the writing.

929
00:49:04,090 --> 00:49:05,002
Rym: Or interleave it back and forth.

930
00:49:06,191 --> 00:49:13,050
Scott: You think, wait a minute, I dragged a file off my USB stick and then dragged a file onto it, and both of the progress meters in Windows moved.

931
00:49:13,352 --> 00:49:14,550
Scott: They moved slow, but they moved.

932
00:49:14,690 --> 00:49:20,388
Scott: It's like, that's right, because what Windows is doing is basically going read, write, read, write, read, write, read, write, read, write, and alternating between the two.

933
00:49:21,033 --> 00:49:28,150
Scott: If you had a USB 3 stick and were using USB 3, both of those would move at full speed because it could read and write simultaneously.

934
00:49:29,350 --> 00:49:42,310
Rym: Now, the reason why sound cards in the old days, even with USB 2, sucked ass, was that because it's not full duplex, it was really hard to have synchronous streams of data.

935
00:49:42,410 --> 00:49:47,589
Rym: There was an isochronous mode that would let you do that, but it wasn't super high bandwidth.

936
00:49:47,775 --> 00:49:47,965
Rym: ASIO.

937
00:49:48,617 --> 00:49:48,989
Rym: Yeah, ISO.

938
00:49:49,578 --> 00:49:50,248
Rym: I-O synchronous.

939
00:49:50,873 --> 00:49:51,309
Scott: ASIO, whatever.

940
00:49:51,550 --> 00:49:52,386
Rym: Yeah, not ASIO.

941
00:49:53,196 --> 00:49:53,510
Scott: Okay.

942
00:49:54,233 --> 00:49:55,890
Rym: That's something different altogether.

943
00:49:56,510 --> 00:49:58,830
Rym: Let's talk about FireWire if you want to get into that business.

944
00:49:59,330 --> 00:50:05,930
Rym: Now, I don't want to talk about the differences between USB and FireWire, but low bandwidth coupled with the fact that there's very high latency.

945
00:50:06,150 --> 00:50:09,330
Rym: USB has latencies, depending on how it's configured, up to a millisecond.

946
00:50:09,470 --> 00:50:23,749
Scott: This is why gaming mice are important to get because latency matters in a gaming application, but it doesn't really matter for printing or a lot of other things, but you need a gaming mouse keyboard mostly because it's going to mitigate USB latency as much as possible.

947
00:50:24,330 --> 00:50:31,570
Rym: Now, depending on what mode the USB is operating in, that is or is not a concern, which is another reason why sometimes you might have issues.

948
00:50:33,090 --> 00:50:41,630
Rym: USB cannot send data at its full rate and send its maximum power at the same time because the power interferes with the data.

949
00:50:42,030 --> 00:50:46,250
Scott: Yeah, even using the two wires for the data is not enough to mitigate a crap ton of interference.

950
00:50:46,350 --> 00:50:47,149
Scott: You can only have so much.

951
00:50:47,391 --> 00:50:55,269
Rym: So that is why some devices, when they're charging, cannot also be used for data transfers or seem really slow suddenly.

952
00:50:57,713 --> 00:51:03,330
Rym: So yeah, the last cool thing I really want to point out is that if you look at USB 3.0 connectors, they're complicated.

953
00:51:03,530 --> 00:51:06,270
Rym: They look almost ghetto and hacked together.

954
00:51:06,390 --> 00:51:11,709
Rym: They look like two connectors kind of stuck onto each other because that's literally what they are.

955
00:51:12,290 --> 00:51:19,070
Rym: A USB 3.0 slot, a B-slot, is a big square with another rectangle hanging off on top of it.

956
00:51:19,450 --> 00:51:24,110
Rym: That way you could plug a USB 2.0 cable into it for backward compatibility.

957
00:51:24,870 --> 00:51:33,969
Rym: Micro 3.0 is a USB micro cable with another ghetto-ass micro 3.0 cable kind of stuck next to it for the same reason.

958
00:51:34,110 --> 00:51:36,390
Scott: This is a pattern you see in a lot of computer cables.

959
00:51:36,490 --> 00:51:47,770
Scott: If you build computers, you'll notice they had ATX power connectors, and then they did ATX+4, which is they had the ATX power connector and then a little four extra thingies hanging off the edge of it to make it bigger when they needed more power.

960
00:51:48,091 --> 00:51:54,929
Rym: Whenever you get a power supply, and then depending on your motherboard and processor, you would break off some of the pins on the end of the power to plug it in.

961
00:51:55,250 --> 00:51:55,319
Scott: Yep.

962
00:51:56,417 --> 00:51:57,389
Rym: Yeah, so it's like that.

963
00:51:58,372 --> 00:52:05,510
